| colspan="3" style="padding:1ex 0 0 0; color:#999999" |<p style="line-height:1em;text-align:right;"><small><cite style="font-style:normal;"> — Claire Priscilla T. Springfield</cite></small></p>
|}
<br><br><br>
<div class="header">Overview</div>
{{Simple Image Block|image=Nuksssiagetyonotes.png|width=400px|caption=<span style="font-size:18px;">An image of the Rice Automatic posted to Backchat, used by expeditioners to defend against entities in [[Level 38.1]].</span>}}
The '''Rice Automatic''', commonly designated the RA100, is a submachine gun chambered in .45 ACP. It was developed by the Liminarmory as their flagship product in 1971 and went on to become one of the most widely used firearms across the Backrooms. Influential Backrooms groups such as the [[M.E.G.|Major Explorer Group]] and [[Republic of Aurielle]] produce licensed copies of the '''Rice Automatic''' under special contracts. 

Its cost-effective and straightforward design allows for somewhat steady mass production by more industrialized Backrooms organizations. Considering many other manmade<ref>Weapons manufactured by wanderers.</ref> ranged weapons in the Backrooms are crossbows, nailguns, air guns, and muskets, the '''Rice Automatic''', firing smokeless powdered-bullets, are relatively advanced. The gun serves as the antithesis to the longer-ranged [[Kalthoff Rifle]], as the '''Rice Automatic''' is best used in close quarters combat encountered in most Backrooms environments.

As Backrooms combat evolves, the '''Rice Automatic''' is slowly declining in usage over the 21st century as many major militaries adopt assault rifles and personal defense weapons. The Liminarmory themselves have minimized production of the SMG since 2010, as they move on to making Kalashnikov replicas. However, due to the cost of servicing such weapons, the uncomplicated submachine gun still stands as an effective, logistics-friendly option despite its underwhelming firepower.
<div class="header">Development and History</div>
{{Simple Image Block|image=NoAImagrips.png|width=400px|caption=<span style="font-size:18px;">First prototype of the Rice, dating back to 1968.</span>}}
{{Simple Image Block|image=Unfortunatelyimstill18.jpg|width=400px|caption=<span style="font-size:18px;">M.E.G. licensed model of the '''Rice Automatic''', designated the Manguerra .45.</span>}}
Up until the 1960s, weapons manufacturing in the Backrooms was relatively primitive as there were no successful attempts at creating smokeless powder cartridges nor any gun that fires them. The Liminarmory was the first known organization to recreate the advanced bullets by recycling spent casings and adding a primer, some propellant, and either a bullet or steel ball akin to ones used by air guns at the time. Only .45 ACP bullets were produced, since it and the 1911 are the most common Backrooms munitions. In the mid 1960s, the Liminarmory began development on a weapon that would complement their .45 ACP restorations, being the '''Rice Automatic'''.

Around the same time, the Republic of Aurielle were developing prototypes of bolt-action rifles which would evolve into the modern [[Kalthoff Rifle]]. The Liminarmory saw an opportunity as they knew well that the Auriellen developments would not suit well to closer ranges, which most Backrooms firefights occur in. Remembering the success of open-bolt submachine guns in the [[Frontrooms]], especially in the [[wp:World War II|Second World War]], work immediately began on an SMG chambered in .45 ACP utilizing said open-bolt mechanisms for a simple and cheap design while still remaining effective. The Liminarmory chose to replicate the M3 Grease Gun, due to its slow fire rate, ergonomic simplicity, and .45 ACP chambering. 

Predicting that the weapon would garner major interest from many clients, the Liminarmory announced that they were developing an open-bolt submachine gun. They manufactured rudimentary prototypes of the submachine gun to bolster public interest. Unsurprisingly, their predictions were met, and the company received major investments from Aurielle, Cascada, the Major Explorer Group, and various others. The investments significantly boosted the company's R&D capabilities, allowing them to further refine the weapon and develop their bullet recycling department to supplement the rising demand for the '''Rice Automatic'''.

When the '''Rice Automatic''' first entered production, demand for the weapon was so high that the Liminarmory's manufacturing capabilities were unable to meet them. To alleviate this issue, the Liminarmory approved licensed copies of the firearm to be developed by major organizations with similar industrial capabilities. Ironically, the initial high demand greatly raised the cost of the weapon, which was counterproductive to the gun's intended purpose. Fortunately, after a few years, as more individuals acquired the weapon, demand and cost mellowed to nominal levels. 

As the '''Rice Automatic''' embarked on a meteoric rise, it was quickly seen among almost every military and human/humanoid fighting force throughout the Backrooms. By 1979, the Liminarmory alone were producing 5,000 examples per year on average for its entire history. Of the smokeless-powdered firearms used in the Backrooms, roughly 35-50% were some variant of the '''Rice Automatic'''. The revenue generated from the submachine gun allowed the Liminarmory to further refine their bullet restorations, as it had multiple issues regarding reliability and stopping power. They also expanded into refurbishing 5.56x45, 7.62x39, .22 Long Rifle, 7.62x51, and .357 Magnum.

Unsurprisingly, many smaller organizations and bandits have tried to make bastardized replicas of the submachine gun which were not as effective and cannot be mass produced. The Liminarmory decided not to take action against these groups as their heavily limited capabilities of recreating the weapon.

With the '''Rice Automatic''' becoming ubiquitous among fighting forces in the Backrooms, it eventually became a symbol for the state of humanity in the Backrooms, showcasing their perseverance and survival when in anomalous conditions, but also the turmoil that erupts when things get too comfortable.

However, the gun is not timeless, and it would be superseded by future developments that solved its glaring issues, mainly its slow rate of fire and weight. The Liminarmory developed experimental variants that boosted its rate of fire to seven hundred rounds per minute, but the power of the .45 ACP cartridge made for troublesome recoil for inexperienced shooters, and increased the strain on the weapon's delicate parts. In the late 1990s, various renowned gunsmiths attempted recreating assault rifles, particularly 7.62x39mm Kalashnikovs, which were successful but cannot see mass production. This was figured out by Aurielle and the M.E.G. by the turn of the millennium.

Despite the onset of assault rifle production among major Backrooms militaries, the '''Rice Automatic''', due to its low cost and simple nature, would remain a staple of fighters until humanity's last conflict in the Backrooms. It is still produced by the Liminarmory until today, with minimal differences from the first renditions in the early 1970s. However, the Liminarmory has released a modernized version with slight weight reduction and modularity for various attachments.
<div class="header">Design Details</div>
{{Simple Image Block|image=Nuksdoyouknowwhataboltis.png|width=400px|caption=<span style="font-size:18px;">A simple schematic detailing the inner workings of the '''Rice Automatic'''.</span>}}
===Overview===
The '''Rice Automatic''' is a blowback-operated submachine gun firing from an open bolt. Both the blowback-operation and open bolt systems are among the most rudimentary firing systems applicable to a repeater firearm. This results in a submachine gun that is extremely simple to mass produce and maintain, placing it within the capability for larger Backrooms societies to engineer and produce. The gun is made entirely of readily available and applicable metals, though steel is prioritized when available. Processes used to manufacture the gun include stamping, welding, and precise machining for the barrel, bolt, and firing mechanism. The ubiquitous usage of metal throughout the gun contributed to its heavy weight, being almost as heavy as the modern [[BRC-TZ]], despite possessing a fraction of the firepower.

===Operating Mechanism===
When a magazine is loaded, the user must cock the bolt to the rear with either a charging crank or via a notch on the bolt carrier itself, directly pulling it back with their finger. Pulling the trigger of the '''Rice Automatic''' frees the bolt from the sear, in which two recoil springs from the rear move it forward, allowing it to guide a bullet from the magazine into the chamber. When the bullet hits the chamber, the bolt's firing pin primes the cartridge, firing the round. This causes a pressure impulse that moves the bolt backward, which is counteracted by the recoil springs. The recoil springs then move the bolt forward to fire another round, repeating the cycle.

===Features===
The submachine gun has a cyclic rate of fire of 450 rounds per minute, due to the low pressure from the .45 ACP cartridge, heavy bolt, and the recoil springs. The slower rate of fire and heavy weight often meant the gun's position would reset before firing the next round, resulting in virtually no recoil. The training needed to adequately operate the weapon was minimal, and some seasoned shooters often dual-wielded the weapon, especially when dealing with swarms of entities. 

The dust cover on the '''Rice Automatic''' also acts as its safety mechanism, as it incorporates a minuscule hook that prevents the bolt from moving. All variants of the submachine gun fire exclusively in fully automatic. 

Telescoping onto the receiver is a rudimentary wire stock, formed from a single steel rod. The stock can be removed from the gun and is viable as a multipurpose tool. It can be used to clean or disassemble the gun. The rear of the stock sports a small hook which can be used as a magazine loader tab.

===Feeding===
The '''Rice Automatic''' feeds from double-stack single-feed 10-, 15-, 20-, 25-, and 30-round box magazines, with 20- and 30- round magazines being the most common. Rarely, 40-, 50-, 60-, 75-, and 100-round drum magazines were manufactured, often used by clients dealing with entity hordes. Due to their cost and low reliability relative to smaller box magazines, drum magazines were not produced by the Liminarmory until 1982. In 2004, the Liminarmory discontinued production of the 10- and 15-round magazines due to minimal usage, and 100-round magazine due to severe reliability issues. It is not advised for a soldier to load a magazine with both refurbished and fresh ammunition due to the inconsistencies between the two, even despite advances in refurbished ammunition.

===Sights===
The sights of the '''Rice Automatic''' consist of a fixed rear aperture sight and a front blade sight, designed for around 60 meters (196 feet). A thicker metal ring is attached to the top of the sight, which a soldier can readily rotate down to increase the sight's range to up to 150 meters (492 feet), though rarely sees usage. The modernized '''Rice Automatic Next-Gen''' (''see Variants'') features a hollow picatinny rail to attach scopes, doubling as a backup iron sight along with the front blade.

===Attachments & Accessories===
Brand new instances of the submachine gun from the Liminarmory often come with a sling, cleaning kit, a bayonet, a magazine coupler, and a magazine loader. Special forces variants with an increase fire rate included a parts kit that were used to change the gun's rate of fire, a cumbersome and stressing task in the heat of battle. The '''Rice Automatic Next-Gen''' included more attachments such as a swappable integral suppressor barrel and optics, but were sold separately.
<div class="header">Variants</div>
{{Simple Image Block|image=UYPILIPINS.webp|width=400px|caption=<span style="font-size:18px;">An older model retrofitted to the next-gen variant featuring a red dot optic, integral suppressor, and forest camo pattern.</span>}}
===Licensed Copies===
In the early days of the '''Rice Automatic'''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s production, the Liminarmory's production capabilities failed to match the high demand of the submachine gun. To alleviate this, the Liminarmory signed contracts with certain groups, allowing them to produce the firearm on their own under a small fee. Instances of the weapon manufactured under these contracts only have minuscule differences from the original version. Examples include the SF series from Aurielle and the M481 from the [[User:ArbiTraitor/AEG_Rewrite|Anti-Entity Group]].

===REX-105===
The '''REX-105''' (Rice Experimental) aimed to solve one of the biggest drawbacks of the submachine gun, its low rate of fire. By changing the bolt and recoil springs, one can boost the fire rate from 450 to 700. These came with major drawbacks, mainly the difficulty to produce, the increased mechanical strain, tendency to jam, and high recoil. Due to the severe drawbacks, this version never saw full production and was completely cancelled only a few years after its conception. Today, it almost never sees usage in combat and is kept in collections and museums. 

===RANG===
Unveiled by the Liminarmory in 2009, the '''Rice Automatic Next-Gen''', shortened to '''RANG''', modernized the aging submachine gun by adding a picatinny rail on top for mounting optics, another on the receiver's left side for mounting an illuminator, and a threaded barrel for muzzle attachments. Additionally, the barrel can be readily swapped<ref>While barrel swapping was featured on older models, the '''RANG''' streamlined the process.</ref>  for a variety of customized ones, including integrally suppressed barrels or barrels with handguards to mount a foregrip. The top-mounted picatinny rail is hollow, allowing a user to utilize it as a backup ironsight. Some were made brand new, while others were retrofitted from already existing instances. Older variants of the '''Rice Automatic''' were fully phased out by 2021 and only this variant saw production.

